12:32.252 --> 12:36.023
I'm sorry, but none
of these girls are right.

12:36.023 --> 12:38.425
None of these girls
are Marilyn, Hef.

12:38.425 --> 12:40.427
They're just not.

12:40.427 --> 12:42.695
But if you want to
print a second issue,

12:42.695 --> 12:44.264
you need to pick
one of them.

12:51.939 --> 12:54.141
Putting Marilyn Monroe
on the cover

12:54.141 --> 12:57.144
had drawn in readers
for the first issue,

12:57.144 --> 13:02.749
but I knew I wasn't going
to find another Marilyn.

13:02.749 --> 13:10.723
If Playboy was going to last
I had to find another hook,

13:10.723 --> 13:13.160
and that's when it hit me.

13:13.160 --> 13:15.228
* Let the sunshine in *

13:15.228 --> 13:17.230
* Come on right away *

13:17.230 --> 13:21.234
* Let the sunshine in,
brighten up my day *

13:21.234 --> 13:24.137
Remember back
in my college days

13:24.137 --> 13:26.006
when I started a column
in the school magazine

13:26.006 --> 13:27.607
called "Co-Ed of the Month"

13:27.607 --> 13:30.443
that featured
female students?

13:30.443 --> 13:33.613
I realized Playboy
could do the same thing,

13:33.613 --> 13:37.550
only we'd call her
the Playmate of the Month.

13:37.550 --> 13:42.722
I had completely forgotten that
the cover of Shaft Magazine

13:42.722 --> 13:47.094
and the feature inside it was
called the Co-Ed of the Month.

13:47.094 --> 13:49.462
It was a revelation.

13:49.462 --> 13:53.733
* And let the sunshine in,
come on right away *

13:53.733 --> 13:57.104
So, a calendar girl
named Margie Harrison

13:57.104 --> 13:58.906
became Miss January.

13:58.906 --> 14:02.910
* Send those clouds away,
let the sunshine in *

14:02.910 --> 14:07.047
Publishing photos
of naked women,

14:07.047 --> 14:08.448
that was nothing new.

14:08.448 --> 14:10.783
It was Hef's personalized
approach to that,

14:10.783 --> 14:12.685
where they
were called Playmates.

14:12.685 --> 14:14.354
This was someone,
your partner in crime.

14:14.354 --> 14:16.656
This was someone
you did things with.

14:16.656 --> 14:18.591
* Girl, you've done me wrong,
that's right *

14:18.591 --> 14:21.694
Was it our best issue? No.

14:21.694 --> 14:23.563
* Yeah, but I really
need you right now *

14:23.563 --> 14:25.132
But I was confident
enough this time

14:25.132 --> 14:27.034
to put my name
and issue number on it.

14:27.034 --> 14:28.868
* Come back to me right now *

14:28.868 --> 14:31.238
* And let the sunshine in *

14:31.238 --> 14:34.307
And believe it or not,
the second issue

14:34.307 --> 14:36.343
outsold the first
by 2,000 copies.

14:36.343 --> 14:38.145
* Brighten up my day *

14:38.145 --> 14:40.180
* Send those clouds away *

14:40.180 --> 14:41.614
* Let the sunshine in *

14:41.614 --> 14:43.616
* Yeah *

14:43.616 --> 14:46.786
Now that our magazine
was a success,

14:46.786 --> 14:50.890
I knew my staff of three
wasn't enough.

14:50.890 --> 14:52.625
**

14:52.625 --> 14:55.028
What do you think
of Playboy?

14:55.028 --> 14:58.631
I think your fiction section
could use a little work.

14:58.631 --> 15:01.068
Oh, really?

15:01.068 --> 15:03.570
When I met Ray Russell,

15:03.570 --> 15:06.806
he was just an unpublished
science fiction writer,

15:06.806 --> 15:10.010
but he'd submitted
a few pieces to the magazine

15:10.010 --> 15:12.745
and I really liked his style.

15:12.745 --> 15:15.949
**

15:15.949 --> 15:17.650
Although his only experience

15:17.650 --> 15:20.020
was writing for
Walgreens circulars,

15:20.020 --> 15:23.423
I made Ray
my associate editor.

15:23.423 --> 15:26.626
My next focus
was the visuals.

15:26.626 --> 15:28.595
**

15:28.595 --> 15:31.031
I had worked with a guy
named Vince Tajiri

15:31.031 --> 15:32.665
during
my publishing house days,

15:32.665 --> 15:36.503
whose talent I felt
was never fully recognized.

15:36.503 --> 15:37.971
**

15:37.971 --> 15:39.439
These days, he was stuck

15:39.439 --> 15:43.376
taking wedding photos
to pay the bills,

15:43.376 --> 15:45.979
so he was more than happy
to accept the position

15:45.979 --> 15:48.381
as Playboy's photo editor.

15:48.381 --> 15:49.616
**

15:49.616 --> 15:52.385
The little magazine
that I had started

15:52.385 --> 15:53.786
with a couple of friends

15:53.786 --> 15:56.990
was suddenly outgrowing
my kitchen table,

15:56.990 --> 15:59.592
so in the spring of 1954,

15:59.592 --> 16:02.862
with the money we had earned
from the first two issues,

16:02.862 --> 16:07.734
Playboy moved
into its own offices.

16:07.734 --> 16:11.238
- Good morning, Mr. Hefner.
- Good morning, Julie.

16:11.238 --> 16:12.705
With our new headquarters...

16:12.705 --> 16:14.141
Eldon.

16:14.141 --> 16:15.608
...my staff was
ready to get to work.

16:15.608 --> 16:18.611
Can I talk to you in
my office? Five minutes?

16:18.611 --> 16:22.549
My dad's success very much
has to do with the fact

16:22.549 --> 16:24.617
that he surrounded himself
with the right people,

16:24.617 --> 16:27.487
and that comes down
to his gut.

16:27.487 --> 16:31.258
His gut allowed him to
figure out who he could trust,

16:31.258 --> 16:35.562
who he couldn't... also to
bring out the best in his team.

16:35.562 --> 16:38.431
**

16:45.538 --> 16:48.075
With our sales growing,

16:48.075 --> 16:51.478
we needed someone to take care
of the subscription requests

16:51.478 --> 16:52.945
that came pouring in.

16:52.945 --> 16:55.682
Hello?
No, of course.

16:55.682 --> 16:57.217
I can do that for you
right now if you like.

16:57.217 --> 16:59.386
So, I hired Charlaine Karalus,

16:59.386 --> 17:01.754
a smart,
determined young woman

17:01.754 --> 17:03.856
with meticulous attention
to detail.

17:03.856 --> 17:05.125
Perfect.
That won't be a problem.

17:05.125 --> 17:08.561
I can get a copy
over to him. Bye.

17:08.561 --> 17:13.300
I had a friend that told me
about Playboy wanting help,

17:13.300 --> 17:17.304
so we decided we would
go for an interview.

17:17.304 --> 17:22.008
Well, we stopped at a newsstand
and we bought the magazine.

17:22.008 --> 17:25.078
She took it real quick
and hid it under her jacket

17:25.078 --> 17:26.679
so no one would see it.

17:26.679 --> 17:30.983
Turned out, my friend
backed out of the interview.

17:30.983 --> 17:33.553
She chickened out
and I didn't.

17:33.553 --> 17:37.390
I had hoped to get
on the ground floor

17:37.390 --> 17:40.493
with this magazine
and grow with them.

17:40.493 --> 17:41.794
**

17:41.794 --> 17:45.165
These various employees
that we're talking about,

17:45.165 --> 17:48.168
one could say
that Hef lucked out

17:48.168 --> 17:52.172
with these guys,
because one never really knows,

17:52.172 --> 17:54.274
but Hefner's gut told him

17:54.274 --> 17:56.843
these were the right people
for the right jobs.

17:56.843 --> 18:00.012
Okay, great, so what's your
turnaround time on that?

18:00.012 --> 18:04.351
I'd assembled a team of
promising, if unproven, talent

18:04.351 --> 18:06.719
but I knew
I needed someone on staff

18:06.719 --> 18:10.157
who could lend a little
credibility to the magazine,

18:10.157 --> 18:14.527
so I hired a guy who had been
an editor at The New Yorker.

18:14.527 --> 18:18.531
His name was
Auguste Comte Spectorsky,

18:18.531 --> 18:23.203
or as we'd soon
call him, Spec.

18:23.203 --> 18:24.537
Hiring Spectorsky

18:24.537 --> 18:26.473
was a brilliant move
on Hefner's part.

18:26.473 --> 18:29.609
Spectorsky gave
the magazine a maturity

18:29.609 --> 18:32.412
it wasn't going to have,
and it's to Hefner's credit

18:32.412 --> 18:37.150
that he understood the magazine
needed that maturity.

18:38.885 --> 18:41.354
**

18:42.722 --> 18:44.391
* Well, rock-a-bye, baby *

18:44.391 --> 18:46.859
I finally had a team in place

18:46.859 --> 18:50.430
and it was time to see
what we could accomplish.

18:50.430 --> 18:51.964
* Rock-a-bye, baby *

18:51.964 --> 18:56.403
* Mama's gonna rock you
by and by *

18:56.403 --> 18:58.104
The staff worked like crazy

18:58.104 --> 18:59.672
to get the magazine
together every month.

18:59.672 --> 19:03.776
* To this little lullaby *

19:03.776 --> 19:05.445
* You don't need
any whiskey *

19:05.445 --> 19:07.414
Day in, day out,

19:07.414 --> 19:10.817
we clocked long hours
and worked weekends.

19:12.785 --> 19:15.788
Playboy was one of
the most exciting places

19:15.788 --> 19:16.889
one could work.

19:16.889 --> 19:20.593
Very different from most
of the other companies

19:20.593 --> 19:24.664
that were around in Chicago
or New York or Los Angeles.

19:26.466 --> 19:29.001
I even bought
a pullout couch for my office

19:29.001 --> 19:30.670
so I could work overnight.

19:30.670 --> 19:33.172
**

19:37.510 --> 19:41.614
I started spending
most of my time at work,

19:41.614 --> 19:43.916
away from my family.

19:43.916 --> 19:48.488
He spent the majority
of his time in that office.

19:48.488 --> 19:50.189
He had a small little bed,

19:50.189 --> 19:52.292
he had a small
little kitchenette,

19:52.292 --> 19:54.327
and he just worked,

19:54.327 --> 20:00.199
and unfortunately, his marriage
suffered from that.

20:02.134 --> 20:05.505
In the marriage, I was
already missing emotionally.

20:05.505 --> 20:10.209
I'm the product of the way
I was raised.

20:10.209 --> 20:13.846
While my father
was absent emotionally,

20:13.846 --> 20:16.182
I was soon absent.

20:16.182 --> 20:19.852
In point of fact,
I wasn't there.

20:21.821 --> 20:23.490
That physical change occurred

20:23.490 --> 20:26.926
because of the success
of the magazine.

20:26.926 --> 20:28.094
It was easier for him

20:28.094 --> 20:31.498
to set up living quarters
somewhere else,

20:31.498 --> 20:34.701
and that's when he said,
"I'm gonna start staying--

20:34.701 --> 20:37.570
living down at the office
a couple of days a week."

20:39.906 --> 20:42.309
**

20:42.309 --> 20:45.878
The team at Playboy
became my other family.

20:45.878 --> 20:49.349
We worked hard,
but we also partied.

20:49.349 --> 20:52.184
And with the magazine's
growing success,

20:52.184 --> 20:56.088
we were getting invited to some
of the best parties in town.

20:56.088 --> 20:59.326
* Let me love you *

20:59.326 --> 21:01.694
And that's where
I was introduced

21:01.694 --> 21:04.564
to a man
named Victor Lownes.

21:04.564 --> 21:05.865
Victor, this is the friend

21:05.865 --> 21:07.367
I was telling you about,
Hugh Hefner.

21:07.367 --> 21:09.201
There you are.
Hi, how are you?

21:09.201 --> 21:10.937
Hef runs the magazine.

21:12.439 --> 21:15.942
Oh, Mr. Playboy.
I like your look.

21:15.942 --> 21:17.209
Nice and casual.

21:17.209 --> 21:19.211
Thank you.
Is this your place?

21:19.211 --> 21:21.548
Yeah, sure is.

21:21.548 --> 21:24.551
When I met Hef,
I thought he was terrific.

21:24.551 --> 21:26.453
Hefner was a very
ambitious businessman,

21:26.453 --> 21:28.254
a very clever businessman.

21:28.254 --> 21:30.723
I mean,
anybody who could start

21:30.723 --> 21:34.727
their own magazine,
I was very impressed.

21:34.727 --> 21:38.831
* If you lend me
your ear... *

21:38.831 --> 21:40.400
It was great
to meet you, Hef,

21:40.400 --> 21:41.868
but I have some
business to attend to.

21:41.868 --> 21:43.570
Um, how about
we grab some drinks

21:43.570 --> 21:45.071
at Walton Walk
on Friday?

21:45.071 --> 21:46.973
Sure.
That sounds good.

21:46.973 --> 21:48.274
Good.

21:48.274 --> 21:50.610
I'll bring along
some friends.

21:50.610 --> 21:52.311
Okay.

21:54.947 --> 21:56.849
For almost a year,

21:56.849 --> 21:59.752
I'd been creating
a magazine called Playboy.

22:01.821 --> 22:04.123
But then one night
at a party,

22:04.123 --> 22:06.092
I actually met one.

22:06.092 --> 22:07.694
**

22:07.694 --> 22:12.765
By 1954, Victor Lownes
was the ultimate bachelor.

22:12.765 --> 22:15.768
He came from a wealthy family
in New York

22:15.768 --> 22:19.539
and was given
anything he wanted.

22:19.539 --> 22:22.775
By the age of 26,
he had moved to Chicago

22:22.775 --> 22:25.177
and was living
the bachelor's dream.

22:25.177 --> 22:29.281
He had the cool apartment,
suave attitude,

22:29.281 --> 22:31.017
and the women.

22:32.885 --> 22:34.921
Victor was leader
of the pack.

22:34.921 --> 22:37.790
Everyone wanted to be
with him, men and women.

22:37.790 --> 22:40.793
He just has this gift of life.

22:40.793 --> 22:44.263
He had great style,
he had great flair.

22:44.263 --> 22:46.699
There was never a dull moment
with Victor Lownes.

22:48.535 --> 22:52.371
I knew Victor could add
something to the magazine,

22:52.371 --> 22:56.142
so I brought him on board
as manager of promotions

22:56.142 --> 22:58.377
and he fit right in.

23:01.881 --> 23:03.983
So, we got two girls, right?

23:03.983 --> 23:06.318
One of 'em puts her leg
across me, right?

23:06.318 --> 23:08.220
Hand underneath.

23:08.220 --> 23:11.123
Victor Lownes played
a great role at the company.

23:11.123 --> 23:16.195
He was something that Hefner
was not-- bold, brash.

23:16.195 --> 23:18.965
He was the complement to Hef,

23:18.965 --> 23:23.402
who was, after all,
a little bit shy and cerebral.

23:23.402 --> 23:25.304
Meanwhile,
I'm at the front, here.

23:25.304 --> 23:28.441
Victor lived the life
most guys dreamed of...

23:28.441 --> 23:30.376
All the way at the front.
Yeah!

23:32.044 --> 23:34.514
...and I wanted
to be a part of it.

23:34.514 --> 23:36.516
**

23:36.516 --> 23:39.719
* She is magic... *

23:39.719 --> 23:40.953
Not even kidding.

23:40.953 --> 23:43.155
No socks, no necktie,
nothing.

23:43.155 --> 23:46.759
I was out with Victor almost
every night of the week.

23:46.759 --> 23:48.861
The guy could get
into any club in Chicago

23:48.861 --> 23:52.965
and always managed to bring
along some incredible company.

23:52.965 --> 23:55.968
I had a very good bond
with Hefner himself.

23:55.968 --> 23:58.270
The two of us worked
late at night

23:58.270 --> 24:01.173
and then we would go out
and have drinks together,

24:01.173 --> 24:05.945
and that became
a regular pattern.

24:05.945 --> 24:07.814
**

24:07.814 --> 24:11.718
Well, we're dancing.

24:11.718 --> 24:15.955
* Fish got to swim
and birds got to fly *

24:15.955 --> 24:17.790
Victor, in some ways,

24:17.790 --> 24:22.495
was more the image
of the editor/publisher

24:22.495 --> 24:24.130
of Playboy than my father was,

24:24.130 --> 24:28.267
because Victor was someone
who loved good food and wine,

24:28.267 --> 24:34.140
who loved to travel, who was
more gregarious and sociable.

24:34.140 --> 24:36.475
**

24:38.578 --> 24:40.747
So, are you gonna ask me
to dance or what?

24:40.747 --> 24:42.815
Oh, of course.

24:42.815 --> 24:45.217
* Tell me he's slow *

24:45.217 --> 24:48.921
Hef really did not
have the example

24:48.921 --> 24:51.123
or the sophistication
growing up

24:51.123 --> 24:55.161
to be what everyone now
thinks of as a playboy.

24:55.161 --> 24:57.496
* Lovin' that man of mine *

24:57.496 --> 25:02.168
It wasn't until his association
with Victor Lownes

25:02.168 --> 25:05.605
that they
almost became a whole.

25:05.605 --> 25:08.808
* He can come home *

25:08.808 --> 25:12.411
* As late as can be *

25:12.411 --> 25:17.984
* Can't help lovin'
that man *

25:17.984 --> 25:22.922
* The way I do *

25:22.922 --> 25:24.591
* Lovin' that man *

25:24.591 --> 25:26.192
Partying with Victor
opened my eyes

25:26.192 --> 25:28.460
to a completely
different world...

25:28.460 --> 25:30.897
**

25:31.998 --> 25:33.566
...and I jumped right in.

25:33.566 --> 25:35.101
* Hey *

25:35.101 --> 25:37.570
**

25:39.572 --> 25:41.173
The beginning of Playboy

25:41.173 --> 25:44.276
introduced me
to a bachelor lifestyle

25:44.276 --> 25:48.114
that has much of the upside
and very few of the downside.

25:48.114 --> 25:51.150
* I want to tell you
a story *

25:51.150 --> 25:52.752
* Every man ought to know *

25:52.752 --> 25:55.121
I felt no guilt
in that context.

25:55.121 --> 25:56.989
I felt that I was exploring
the outer limits

25:56.989 --> 25:59.225
of what it meant
to really be moral.

25:59.225 --> 26:01.327
But the truth of the matter is,
I was running away,

26:01.327 --> 26:06.232
I think,
from my traditional values.

26:06.232 --> 26:07.634
* Hey hey hey *

26:07.634 --> 26:09.401
**

26:09.401 --> 26:12.772
You have to remember,
this was the 1950s.

26:12.772 --> 26:14.206
You were supposed
to get married

26:14.206 --> 26:16.909
and start a family
right after school.

26:16.909 --> 26:20.046
But times were changing.

26:20.046 --> 26:22.114
My father had a sense

26:22.114 --> 26:24.116
that he wanted more
out of life

26:24.116 --> 26:26.753
than he had seen
his father get out of life,

26:26.753 --> 26:28.755
and that a part
of that was the idea

26:28.755 --> 26:30.156
of having a period of time

26:30.156 --> 26:32.324
before you got married
and settled down.

26:32.324 --> 26:35.527
And he got married young,
and I think, too young,

26:35.527 --> 26:37.263
and he would say that.

26:37.263 --> 26:38.698
* Hey *

26:38.698 --> 26:40.366
* Hey hey hey *

26:40.366 --> 26:42.034
As I began spending
more of my time

26:42.034 --> 26:44.336
living the life
of a single man,

26:44.336 --> 26:48.040
I realized it was time to
update the magazine's message.

26:48.040 --> 26:49.976
* Oh work it now,
work that *

26:49.976 --> 26:53.646
When I started Playboy,
it was filled with topics

26:53.646 --> 26:55.181
that met my interests.

26:55.181 --> 26:56.749
* Hey *

26:56.749 --> 26:58.084
* Oh, work it now *

26:58.084 --> 27:01.353
But now I wanted to do more.

27:01.353 --> 27:04.423
I wanted to turn the magazine
into a guide

27:04.423 --> 27:07.326
for how to become
the ultimate playboy.

27:09.896 --> 27:11.898
What is a playboy?

27:14.266 --> 27:16.168
Just toss out a word.

27:16.168 --> 27:17.670
A bachelor.

27:17.670 --> 27:19.772
What else?

27:19.772 --> 27:21.073
Suave.

27:21.073 --> 27:22.474
Sophisticated.

27:22.474 --> 27:24.811
- Intelligent.
- Urbane.

27:24.811 --> 27:26.278
Right.

27:26.278 --> 27:30.216
Every time someone
picks up a copy of Playboy,

27:30.216 --> 27:33.585
I don't want him to just
imagine himself

27:33.585 --> 27:36.388
as the type of guy
who can get the girl he wants.

27:36.388 --> 27:38.925
I want to teach him how.

27:38.925 --> 27:40.760
How to buy
the right suit,

27:40.760 --> 27:42.428
select the right
bottle of wine,

27:42.428 --> 27:45.097
put on the right music
when a girl comes over.

27:45.097 --> 27:48.300
I don't want to
follow trends.

27:48.300 --> 27:50.236
I want to create them.

27:50.236 --> 27:53.439
And that is why
every article, every picture,

27:53.439 --> 27:56.876
every page must be
specifically tailored

27:56.876 --> 28:00.947
to promote this one,
singular vision...

28:00.947 --> 28:04.183
the Playboy lifestyle.

28:06.819 --> 28:09.421
The message was very clear.

28:09.421 --> 28:13.559
We were talking about how
to live as a single male.

28:13.559 --> 28:14.961
And nobody had done that before.

28:14.961 --> 28:17.529
* My sugar is so... *

28:17.529 --> 28:20.499
My staff had
their marching orders,

28:20.499 --> 28:22.368
and we worked
around the clock,

28:22.368 --> 28:24.871
redefining every section
of the magazine

28:24.871 --> 28:28.574
to promote
the Playboy lifestyle.

28:28.574 --> 28:30.409
* She goes to see... *

28:30.409 --> 28:32.644
Tajiri translated
his slick photographic style

28:32.644 --> 28:34.546
into how-to guides...

28:36.282 --> 28:40.686
...teaching our readers to
select the finest in fashion,

28:40.686 --> 28:43.255
mix the perfect cocktail,

28:43.255 --> 28:46.225
outfit the most
cutting-edge bachelor pad

28:46.225 --> 28:50.262
and orchestrate
the perfect date.

28:50.262 --> 28:53.800
* She says "toh-mah-toh"
instead of "toh-may-toh" *

28:53.800 --> 28:56.402
There's a generation
of men who said,

28:56.402 --> 28:58.004
"I'm not gonna marry
the girl down the street

28:58.004 --> 29:00.739
and I'm gonna
move to a major city."

29:00.739 --> 29:03.742
That really shook up America

29:03.742 --> 29:07.113
and I think that bred
the ground for Hef to come out

29:07.113 --> 29:09.782
and invent the idea
of the bachelor.

29:09.782 --> 29:11.884
* We'll be married soon *

29:11.884 --> 29:14.553
I think the thing that made
Playboy so special

29:14.553 --> 29:17.790
was that we managed
to mix the lifestyle

29:17.790 --> 29:19.191
and the sexual content

29:19.191 --> 29:22.094
with a mix of
contemporary values

29:22.094 --> 29:23.595
that were not really
getting expression

29:23.595 --> 29:25.497
in other mass media.

29:25.497 --> 29:28.267
**

29:31.237 --> 29:33.973
Our readership
continued to expand...

29:33.973 --> 29:35.507
Yeah, it's nice,
it's nice.

29:35.507 --> 29:37.543
...and I realized
that we were no longer

29:37.543 --> 29:39.078
just a magazine.

29:39.078 --> 29:41.280
We were becoming a brand.

29:42.949 --> 29:45.517
But there was still
one thing missing.

29:45.517 --> 29:48.720
Playboy needed a logo.

29:48.720 --> 29:51.123
**

29:52.791 --> 29:55.427
So I gave Art Paul
the task of designing it.

29:55.427 --> 29:57.363
**

29:57.363 --> 30:00.499
* Talk to me, baby,
whisper in my ear *

30:00.499 --> 30:02.134
Four minutes later,

30:02.134 --> 30:04.070
he had sketched
the perfect symbol...

30:04.070 --> 30:06.906
* Talk to me, baby,
whisper in my ear *

30:06.906 --> 30:11.077
...an image so flawless
that even 60 years later,

30:11.077 --> 30:12.678
it remains
completely unchanged.

30:12.678 --> 30:15.314
* Don't have no fear *

30:15.314 --> 30:20.019
* Don't you know
I love you so *

30:20.019 --> 30:22.354
The Playboy
rabbit head is iconic.

30:22.354 --> 30:26.725
It is one of a handful
of symbols that,

30:26.725 --> 30:29.695
from very early on, became
phenomenally recognizable.

30:29.695 --> 30:32.831
* Holler hey, hey *

30:32.831 --> 30:34.500
* Kokomo *

30:34.500 --> 30:36.202
**

30:36.202 --> 30:39.939
Our famous mascot
became a part of every issue,

30:39.939 --> 30:42.708
with Art Paul
turning it into a game,

30:42.708 --> 30:44.110
challenging our readers

30:44.110 --> 30:47.479
to find the rabbit
hidden on every cover.

30:47.479 --> 30:49.916
**

30:56.788 --> 31:00.226
* There's dimples
on her elbows *

31:00.226 --> 31:02.494
The best comparison
I have for Hef,

31:02.494 --> 31:04.130
I would say Hefner
is Walt Disney

31:04.130 --> 31:06.032
and the bunny
is his Mickey Mouse.

31:06.032 --> 31:08.134
* Dimples on her knees *

31:08.134 --> 31:10.336
It's branding.
It's marketing. It's brilliance.

31:10.336 --> 31:12.804
* She chills and thrills me *

31:12.804 --> 31:16.042
* With just
a little squeeze **

31:17.876 --> 31:21.547
* I like the sleigh ride,
I like the sleigh ride *

31:21.547 --> 31:25.684
* Jingle bells,
jingle bells *

31:25.684 --> 31:26.818
* Jingle all the way *

31:26.818 --> 31:29.121
Pass these around,
gentlemen.

31:29.121 --> 31:34.493
Looking back, 1954 had been
an incredible year.

31:34.493 --> 31:37.796
The magazine I'd started
with a staff of three

31:37.796 --> 31:42.268
had taken over four floors
of a Chicago office building,

31:42.268 --> 31:45.004
hired over 25 employees,

31:45.004 --> 31:50.509
and grown monthly sales
to nearly 185,000 copies,

31:50.509 --> 31:52.178
more than doubling
the print-run

31:52.178 --> 31:54.646
of our first issue.

31:54.646 --> 31:57.683
It's really remarkable
the magazine was profitable

31:57.683 --> 32:01.287
in its first year.
Nobody does that.

32:01.287 --> 32:03.355
Sports Illustrated,
for a frame of reference,

32:03.355 --> 32:05.657
started about the same time
as Playboy,

32:05.657 --> 32:08.427
and they didn't turn a profit
until the early '60s.

32:08.427 --> 32:11.097
* I like the sleigh ride **

32:12.431 --> 32:14.933
**

32:16.302 --> 32:21.773
* Silent night *

32:21.773 --> 32:26.812
* Holy night *

32:26.812 --> 32:32.384
* All is calm *

32:32.384 --> 32:37.223
* All is bright *

32:37.223 --> 32:42.394
* Round yon virgin *

32:42.394 --> 32:47.699
* Mother and child *

32:47.699 --> 32:50.169
**

32:53.039 --> 32:55.241
My father wasn't
around a lot

32:55.241 --> 32:56.975
when I was growing up.

32:58.710 --> 33:02.881
Putting the magazine first,
which Hef clearly did,

33:02.881 --> 33:05.584
meant, by definition,
that he wasn't gonna have

33:05.584 --> 33:08.220
the same kind of family life
that he would have

33:08.220 --> 33:09.755
if he hadn't done that.

33:09.755 --> 33:12.224
**

33:16.795 --> 33:20.266
He was so busy with the company,
he didn't have a lot of time,

33:20.266 --> 33:22.934
but he was Daddy,
and Daddy was good,

33:22.934 --> 33:25.937
and Daddy was caring.

33:25.937 --> 33:28.540
**

33:28.540 --> 33:31.577
But he was
fairly non-existent.

33:31.577 --> 33:34.046
**

33:35.781 --> 33:39.151
I knew I should have
been home with my family

33:39.151 --> 33:42.454
to be the father
Christie needed,

33:42.454 --> 33:44.690
but there was always
something at the office

33:44.690 --> 33:47.193
that pulled me away.

33:48.727 --> 33:50.196
All right, so you
can see we're going

33:50.196 --> 33:51.763
for a beach theme here.

33:51.763 --> 33:53.999
We're incorporating an image
of the bunny in the sand,

33:53.999 --> 33:56.135
making use
of the bathing suit,

33:56.135 --> 33:57.669
and you can see there's
just a pair of legs

33:57.669 --> 34:00.706
walking into the distance,
suggesting that it may be

34:00.706 --> 34:02.474
her suit that we're seeing,
which of course

34:02.474 --> 34:05.744
would mean that she's not
wearing anything at all.

34:10.182 --> 34:12.651
Uh, it was just an idea.

34:12.651 --> 34:14.653
I can come up with
a couple other options

34:14.653 --> 34:17.356
if you're not happy
with it, Hef.

34:17.356 --> 34:20.426
No, no. It's a good cover.
It's a great cover.

34:20.426 --> 34:22.561
